<subsection xml:id="subsec-laws-of-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Laws of indices</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            The laws of indices, also known as the laws of exponents, are fundamental rules that govern the manipulation of expressions involving powers or indices.
            These laws are essential for simplifying calculations and solving equations involving exponential terms. Here are the key laws of indices:
        </p>
        <p>
            1. <m>\textbf{Product of Powers}</m>: When multiplying two expressions with the same base, you add the exponents:
            <m>a^m \cdot a^n = a^{m+n}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. <m>\textbf{Quotient of Powers}</m>: When dividing two expressions with the same base, you subtract the exponents:
            <m>\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            3. <m>\textbf{Power of a Power}</m>: When raising an expression with an exponent to another exponent, you multiply the exponents:
            <m>(a^m)^n = a^{m \times n}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            4. <m>\textbf{Power of a Product}</m>: When raising a product to an exponent, you raise each factor to the exponent:
            <m>(ab)^n = a^n \times b^n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            5. <m>\textbf{Power of a Quotient}</m>: When raising a quotient to an exponent, you raise both the numerator and denominator to the exponent:
            <m>\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)^n = \frac{a^n}{b^n}</m>, where <m>b \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            6. <m>\textbf{Zero Exponent}</m>: Any non-zero base raised to the power of zero is equal to one:
            <m>a^0 = 1</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            7. <m>\textbf{Negative Exponent}</m>: A negative exponent indicates the reciprocal of the base raised to the absolute value of the exponent:
            <m>a^{-n} = \frac{1}{a^n}</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-multiplication-law-of-indices">
        <title>Multiplication law of indices</title>
        <p>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            The multiplication law of indices states that when you multiply two numbers with the same base, you add their exponents. 
            This can be expressed mathematically as:
            <m>a^m \times a^n = a^{m+n}</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are the exponents.
        </p>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In groups of <m>5</m>, use numbers between <m>1</m> and <m>9</m> to form at least three pairs of numbers that have the same base but different powers.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Multiply each pair that you have formed.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Example: <m>2^2 \times 2^3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Simplify each expression using the multiplication law of indices.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Discuss your work with your fellow learners.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p>
                   a) <m>2^3 \times 2^4</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                   b) <m>8^3 \times 8^6</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                   a) Since the bases are the same, we can apply the multiplication law of indices:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>2^3 \times 2^4 = 2^{3+4} </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m> = 2^7</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    b) Similarly, for the second expression:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>8^3 \times 8^6 = 8^{3+6} </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m> = 8^9</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate: <m>4x^3 \times 7x^2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we can multiply the coefficients (the numbers in front):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>4 \times 7 = 28</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we apply the multiplication law of indices to the variable <m>x</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>x^3 \times x^2 = x^{3+2} = x^5</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                     Combining them we have: <m> 28x^5</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>4x^3 \times 7x^2 = 28x^5</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-division-law-of-indices">
        <title>Division law of indices</title>
        <p>
            The division law of indices states that when you divide two numbers with the same base, you subtract their exponents. 
            This can be expressed mathematically as:
            <m>\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are the exponents.
        </p>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Using the division law of indices, work with the following pairs of numbers:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               i) <m>5^2 , 5^1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               ii) <m>2^3, 2^5</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               iii) <m>4^4, 4^8</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                iv) <m>6^6, 6^3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               For each pair above, form a division expression.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Example: <m>5^2 \div 5^1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Now apply the division law of indices to simplify each expression you created.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Then, create one division expression of your own using the law of indices. Simplify and calculate it.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Share your work with your fellow learners.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p>
                     a) <m>\frac{5^6}{5^2}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                        b) <m>\frac{10^5}{10^3}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                   a) To solve for <m>\frac{5^6}{5^2}</m>, we apply the division law of indices:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{5^6}{5^2} = 5^{6-2} </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>= 5^4</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    b) Solving <m>\frac{10^5}{10^3}</m>, we have:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{10^5}{10^3} = 10^{5-3} </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>= 10^2</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate: <m>\frac{3x^5}{9x^2}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we can simplify the coefficients:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{3}{9} = \frac{1}{3}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we apply the division law of indices to the variable <m>x</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^5}{x^2} = x^{5-2} = x^3</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Combining them we have: <m> \frac{1}{3}x^3</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>\frac{3x^5}{9x^2} = \frac{1}{3}x^3</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-brackets-with-indices">
        <title>Brackets with indices</title>
        <p>
           Brackets with indices are where we have a term inside a bracket with an index (or power) outside of the bracket. 
        </p>
        <p>
           Example: <m>(a^2)^3 = a^{2 \times 3} = a^6</m> 
        </p>
        <p>
            In general when there is a term inside a bracket with an index (or power) outside of the bracket multiply the powers.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>(a^m)^n = a^{m×n}=a^{mn}</m>
        </p>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Working in groups of <m>5</m>, consider the following expressions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="a)">
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                           <m>(2^3)^2</m> 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(3^2)^3</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(5^1)^4</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(4^2)^1</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(10^2)^3</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(7^3)^2</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Recall the bracket law of indices and simplify the expressions above.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Share your work with your fellow learners
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is <m>(5^3)^3?</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>(5^3)^3</m> is given by multiplying the powers:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>3 \times 3 = 9</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Hence, <m>(5^3)^3 = 5^9</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the expression <m>(4y^2)^3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                   <m>(4y^2)^3</m> can be written as <m>4^3 \times (y^2)^3</m> 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Solving for <m> (y^2)^3</m>, we have:
                </p>
                <p>
                   <m> (y^2)^3 = y^{ 2 \times 3} = y^6</m> 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Hence, <m>(y^2)^3 = y^6</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we compute <m>4^3</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>4^3 = 4 \times 4 \times 4 = 64 </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>(4y^2)^3</m> <m>= 64y^6</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
    
</subsection>